Priority-score formulas (2–3 options)
Formula 1: Multiplicative gap-weighting (simple, strong, and intuitive)
This is the cleanest expression of your intent.
PriorityScore = Urgency × GapWeight(response)
Where:
GapWeight(No) = 1.0


GapWeight(Somewhat) = 0.5


GapWeight(Yes) = 0.0 (or 0.1 if you never want “Yes” to be truly zero)


Effect
“No” items rise to the top in proportion to urgency.


“Somewhat” items still matter, but are consistently lower than “No” at the same urgency.


“Yes” sinks (and can be fully pushed to the bottom if you use 0.0).


When to use
If the report is meant to highlight gaps, not reinforce strengths.



Formula 2: Gap points based on your 0/1/2 scoring (smooth and normalized)
This uses the scoring system you already have.
Let:
MaxPoints = 2


ResponsePoints ∈ {0,1,2} for {No, Somewhat, Yes}


GapPoints = (MaxPoints − ResponsePoints) ∈ {2,1,0}


Optional normalization: GapPct = GapPoints / MaxPoints ∈ {1.0, 0.5, 0.0}


Then:
PriorityScore = Urgency × GapPct
This is basically Formula 1, but it’s “derived” from the scoring system rather than hardcoding weights.
Effect
Same behavior as Formula 1, but more defensible: “We prioritize based on urgency times gap from target.”


When to use
If you want the priority definition to be explainable in one sentence without extra rules.



