Canonical ranking spec (SQL definition)
Below is the canonical ordering expressed in SQL terms. This is written to be implemented as a view (or materialized view) in Supabase.
Required fields referenced
user_id (or assessment_id)


checkpoint_id


dimension_id


urgency_score


response_points (0/1/2)


default_dimension_rank (int; static per checkpoint within its dimension)


SQL pattern (conceptual, Supabase/Postgres)
WITH scored AS (
  SELECT
    r.assessment_id,
    c.checkpoint_id,
    c.dimension_id,
    c.capability_area_id,
    c.checkpoint_title,
    c.checkpoint_description,

    c.urgency_score,

    /* assessment response mapped to points */
    r.response_points, -- 0=no, 1=somewhat, 2=yes

    /* tier rule: push YES to bottom */
    CASE
      WHEN r.response_points = 2 THEN 3  -- Yes
      WHEN r.response_points = 1 THEN 2  -- Somewhat
      ELSE 1                              -- No
    END AS response_tier,

    c.default_dimension_rank

  FROM assessment_checkpoint_responses r
  JOIN checkpoints c
    ON c.checkpoint_id = r.checkpoint_id

  /* Important: ensure this is already stage-calibrated */
  WHERE r.assessment_id = :assessment_id
    AND c.stage_id = :stage_id
),

ranked AS (
  SELECT
    *,
    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (
      PARTITION BY assessment_id, dimension_id
      ORDER BY
        response_tier ASC,
        urgency_score DESC,
        response_points ASC,
        default_dimension_rank ASC
    ) AS rank_in_dimension
  FROM scored
)

SELECT *
FROM ranked
ORDER BY dimension_id, rank_in_dimension;

Notes for implementation (handoff-friendly)
Stage calibration: the WHERE c.stage_id = :stage_id (or equivalent join to an assessment stage field) is what guarantees each respondent only ranks their 125 checkpoints.


Determinism: the default_dimension_rank is required so you never have “random” ordering when urgency/response are identical.


No need for a single numeric “priority score”: the ordering above is the priority definition, and it’s easier to explain, debug, and trust than a blended formula.


Rank stability for merges: since the output is always rank_in_dimension = 1..25, your Google Docs template can reliably map to DimX_Row01..Row25.

