Store the fallback rank as a column on the stage-calibrated checkpoint record (i.e., on checkpoint_stage.default_dimension_rank).
 No separate “universal table” is required unless you want extra governance/versioning.
Why it should live on the checkpoint record (recommended)
Simplest SQL: the tie-break is just the last ORDER BY key.


Deterministic by design: every checkpoint already “knows” its fallback position.


Easy to maintain: you can edit the tie-break order in one table without managing joins.


Stage-specific compatibility: because you have ~125 per stage (≈500 total), the fallback order must be valid within that stage’s dimension set anyway. Putting it on checkpoint_stage avoids accidentally applying a “universal” order that doesn’t match that stage’s wording/structure.


How ties are actually handled (important nuance)
You don’t need SQL to explicitly “detect ties.” You simply define a stable ordering:
ORDER BY
  response_tier ASC,
  urgency_score DESC,
  response_points ASC,
  default_rank ASC

If two checkpoints have the same urgency_score and the same response (same response_tier / response_points), Postgres will naturally fall through to the next sort key, default_dimension_rank.
So the tie-break logic works automatically; no IF statements required.
Addendum — Fallback Rank Order (Tie-Break Logic)
Purpose
 Ensure that checkpoint ranking is fully deterministic, stable, and auditable, even when multiple checkpoints share the same urgency score and response state.
Design Decision
 The fallback (tie-break) rank order is stored directly on the stage-calibrated checkpoint record, not in a separate universal table.
Implementation
Field name: checkpoint_stage.default_dimension_rank


Type: Integer


Scope: Unique within each (stage_id, dimension_id)


Each stage-specific checkpoint is assigned a predefined position that represents its canonical fallback order within its Dimension for that stage. This value is only used when all higher-priority ranking criteria are equal.
How It’s Used in Ranking
 The SQL ranking logic does not explicitly detect ties. Instead, it relies on a stable, ordered sort sequence:
response_tier (No → Somewhat → Yes)


urgency_score (DESC)


response_points (ASC)


default_dimension_rank (ASC) ← fallback


When two checkpoints have identical urgency and response values, the system automatically falls through to default_dimension_rank to resolve ordering.
Why This Approach
Keeps ranking logic simple and transparent


Avoids unnecessary joins or lookup tables


Supports stage-specific calibration (125 checkpoints per stage)


Allows easy maintenance or refinement of fallback order


Guarantees consistent output for report merges and dashboards


Data Integrity Requirement
Enforce a uniqueness constraint on
 (stage_id, dimension_id, default_dimension_rank)
 to prevent ambiguous tie-breaks.


This ensures that every checkpoint has a deterministic position in the ranked list under all conditions.
